`eval` and `exec` are for dynamically executing Python code, either simple expressions or compound statements (respectively).

[So, one practical example from the standard library, `collections.namedtuple` uses `exec` to dynamically define a `__new__` method for the tuple subclass being returned:][1]


    # Create all the named tuple methods to be added to the class namespace
    
    s = f&#39;def __new__(_cls, {arg_list}): return _tuple_new(_cls, ({arg_list}))&#39;
    namespace = {&#39;_tuple_new&#39;: tuple_new, &#39;__name__&#39;: f&#39;namedtuple_{typename}&#39;}
    # Note: exec() has the side-effect of interning the field names
    exec(s, namespace)
    __new__ = namespace[&#39;__new__&#39;]
    __new__.__doc__ = f&#39;Create new instance of {typename}({arg_list})&#39;
    if defaults is not None:
        __new__.__defaults__ = defaults

  [1]: https://github.com/python/cpython/blob/master/Lib/collections/__init__.py#L379


This sometimes makes sense, however, this is often abused by inexperience programmers to write unnecessarily dynamic code, e.g. dynamically creating a bunch of variables, when they should have used a `list` or a `dict` (or some other container) instead.

I don&#39;t know why you are trying to do this or whether it will work correctly at all, but the particular error you are observing right now is because MPI is a C library.

C++ treats C entities separately from C++ entities. So if you declare a function `MPI_Allreduce` in C++ code it does not refer to the same function `MPI_Allreduce` that you would have gotten if you used the same declaration in C code.

In order to make a name refer to the C entity, you have to declare it with C language linkage, which is done with

    extern &quot;C&quot; {
        // declarations go here
    }

You can look into `mpi.h` to see that it does the same thing.

