You SHOULD NOT be mutating DOM in a service. You should mutate DOM in the component, and if the state of an element is shared, you should keep track of the state in the service. The code is untestable because it is anti-pattern.

What you should do, instead, is keep state in the service. You can use a variable or a `BehaviorSubject` for this:

### Variable

(Don&#39;t recommend using. This can have potential race conditions)

```lang-javascript
// my-service.js
public gridVisible = false
```

```lang-javascript
// my-component.ts
export class Component implements OnInit {

    constructor(public myService: MyService){};

    toggleGrid(visible: boolean) {
        this.myService.gridVisible = visible;
    }
}
```

```lang-html
&lt;div v-if=&quot;myService.gridVisible&quot;&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
```

### BehaviorSubject

```lang-javascript
// my-service.js
public gridVisible: BehaviorSubject&lt;boolean&gt; = false
```

```lang-javascript
// my-component.ts
export class Component implements OnInit {

    constructor(public myService: MyService){};

    toggleGrid(visible: boolean) {
        this.myService.gridVisible.next(visible);
    }
}
```

```lang-html
&lt;div v-if=&quot;myService.gridVisible | async&quot;&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
```

&lt;hr/&gt;

It is then sufficient to test whether `gridVisible` affects the DOM **in the component tests**. This should be easy because you will obviously have access to the component in the component tests.

Angular provides very consistent and easy-to-use two-way data-binding. Don&#39;t try to use vanilla JS to manipulate the DOM; this can lead to unexpected results.

